d 'LWDID': module to implmenent Rolling Difference-in-Differences Estimator for Small-N and Large-N Panel Data
d
d      lwdid implements the transformation-based rolling
d Difference-in-Differences estimators developed in Lee and
d Wooldridge (2025,    2026a).	The command provides a unified
d implementation for panel data settings with either a large-N or a
d small-N    cross-sectional dimension, allowing treatment effects
d to be estimated under both the staggered treatment adoption and
d the common	timing case.	The central idea is to transform
d outcomes within each unit to remove pre-treatment means, trends,
d or seasonal components,    yielding residualized outcomes. These
d transformed outcomes allow treatment effects to be estimated
d using simple cross-sectional	  regressions in each
d post-treatment period, facilitating both overall and
d period-specific ATT estimation.    By default, lwdid uses the
d large-N procedure of Lee and Wooldridge (2025), which is designed
d for panels with a large    cross-sectional dimension and allows
d for heterogeneous treatment effects and unit-specific
d heterogeneous linear trends.	  When the cross-sectional
d dimension is small (small-N), conventional large-N inference may
d be unreliable. In such settings,    specifying the small option
d invokes the exact small-sample inference procedures developed in
d Lee and Wooldridge (2026a). The    seasonal-adjustment options
d demeanq, detrendq, demeanm, and detrendm are currently available
d only under the small-N    implementation.    Based on the
d treatment cohort variable specified in gvar(), lwdid
d automatically detects whether the design involves a single   
d treatment cohort (common timing) or multiple cohorts (staggered
d adoption) and applies the appropriate estimation procedure. 
d
d KW: DiD
d KW: panel data
d KW: treatment effects
d
d Requires: Stata version 16
d
d Distribution-Date: 20260428
d
d Author: Soo Jeong Lee,  Southern Illinois University Carbondale
d Support: email soojeong.lee@@siu.edu
d
d Author: Jeffrey M. Wooldridge, Michigan State University
d Support: email  wooldri1@@msu.edu
d
f lwdid.ado
f lwdid.sthlp
f lw_castle.dta
